'''Customer lifecycle management''' or '''CLM''' is the measurement of multiple customer-related [[Performance metric|metrics]], which, when analyzed for a period of time, indicate performance of a business. The overall scope of the CLM implementation process encompasses all domains or departments of an organization, which generally brings all sources of static and dynamic [[data]], [[marketing]] processes, and value added services to a unified decision supporting platform through iterative phases of customer acquisition, retention, cross and up-selling, and lapsed customer win-back.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realmarket.com/required/rappdigital4.pdf |accessdate=September 21, 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030519132836/http://www.realmarket.com/required/rappdigital4.pdf |archivedate= May 19, 2003| title=e-Marketing Fundamentals: the Customer Relationship Curve|author=Mark D. Thompson |publisher=RappDigital, Inc. }}</ref>
Some detailed CLM models further breakdown these phases into acquisition, introduction to products, profiling of customers, growth of customer base, cultivation of loyalty among customers, and termination of customer relationship.{{cn|date=January 2016|reason = dead link restore}}
According to a DM Review magazine article by [[Claudia Imhoff]], [[et al.]], "The purpose of the customer life cycle is to define and communicate the stages through which a customer progresses when considering, purchasing and using products, and the associated business processes a company uses to move the customer through the customer life cycle."<ref>{{cite web |authors=Claudia Imhoff, [[Jonathan G. Geiger]], [[Lisa Loftis]] |title=Building the Customer-Centric Enterprise |publisher=DM Review Magazine |date=November 2002 |url=http://www.dmreview.com/issues/20001101/2813-1.html |accessdate=2008-11-04}}</ref>
